      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Eugene O'Neill (1888-1953) was an American dramatist and winner of the 1936 Nobel Prize for Literature. Among his best-known 
	  works are <emph render="italic">Desire Under the Elms</emph>, <emph render="italic">Mourning Becomes Electra</emph>, and 
	  the semi-autobiographical <emph render="italic">Long Day's Journey Into Night</emph>.</p>
	  <p>Earle B. Mayfield (1881-1964) was an American attorney and United States Senator from Texas.  John S. Mayfield, American 
	  bibliographer and book collector, was his son.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">John Mayfield Collection Relating to Eugene O'Neill</emph> consists of correspondence, 
		 printed material and writings.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> consists primarily of correspondence between Mayfield and others relating 
		 to his publication of five letters from O'Neill to Mayfield's father, Texas senator Earle B. Mayfield.  Photostats of the 
		 letters 
		 are included in the collection.  There is also correspondence between John Mayfield and O'Neill's widow, Carlotta O'Neill. 
		 Other correspondents include O'Neill biographer Louis Sheaffer and Earle B. Mayfield.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Printed material</emph> consists of newspaper clippings about O'Neill on the occasion of his death 
		 and one about his wife Carlotta's death, and a variety of items such as a cartoon, a program for a production of 
		 <emph render="italic">Long Day's Journey Into Night</emph>, and so on.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Writings</emph> contains drafts, proofs and final published versions of Mayfield's 
		 "Eugene O'Neill and the Senator from Texas," and one copy of Mayfield's "Black Badge of Treason" (about Ezra Pound).</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>Correspondence is arranged chronologically.  The other series are in no particular order.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
